---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const issueUrl =
  'https://github.com/gronnerup/fabricstack/issues/new?template=submit-tool.yml';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Submit a tool"
  description="How to submit a tool to the fabricstack catalog via a GitHub Issue Form."
>
  <div class="max-w-2xl prose prose-zinc dark:prose-invert">
    <h1>Submit a tool</h1>
    <p>
      fabricstack is curated against published <a href="/criteria">inclusion
      criteria</a>. Submissions are made through a GitHub Issue Form, reviewed by
      the site maintainer, and, if approved, added to the catalog via a pull
      request.
    </p>

    <h2>Before you submit</h2>
    <p>To be eligible, a tool must:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Be specifically built for, or directly useful to, Microsoft Fabric and/or Power BI development.</li>
      <li>Be publicly accessible (not internal-only or behind a private agreement).</li>
      <li>
        Be an actual <strong>tool</strong> (a CLI, SDK, API, MCP server,
        library, framework, extension, app, template, or hosted service) and
        <strong>not</strong> a blog post, course, book, video, or tutorial.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Documentation, active maintenance, and a free tier are <em>not</em>
      required. Deprecated tools stay in the catalog with a badge.
    </p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Open the submission form and fill in the tool's details.</li>
      <li>The maintainer reviews it against the criteria.</li>
      <li>
        Approved tools are merged and deploy within about a minute. Declined
        submissions are closed with a comment referencing the criterion that
        wasn't met.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p class="not-prose mt-8">
      <a
        href={issueUrl}
        class="inline-flex rounded-md bg-accent px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-accent-contrast hover:opacity-90"
      >
        Open the submission form on GitHub →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2>Edits & deprecations</h2>
    <p>
      Spotted something out of date? Every tool's detail page has a
      <strong>Suggest edit</strong> link that opens GitHub's editor for that
      file, so you can propose a change as a pull request directly.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
